{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9273cd4f-426f-41ee-afe2-26acf1f987c0","content":"## What's happening\n\n**.NET 11 raised the minimum x86-64 microarchitecture level** on Linux from **x86-64-v1** (original amd64) to **x86-64-v2**. The runtime now performs a startup check and refuses to run if the CPU lacks required instructions.\n\n**x86-64-v2 requires:** SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, and CMPXCHG16B — instruction sets that became standard around Intel Nehalem/Westmere (2008–2010) and AMD Bulldozer (2011). However, some 2012-era CPUs (especially older AMD families or low-power Intel Atom parts from that era) may still lack one or more of these.\n\n## Why only that node fails\n\n| Target | Status | Why |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Linux x86-64 (new hardware)** | ✅ | Modern CPUs have had v2 instructions for years |\n| **Linux x86-64 (2012 node)** | ❌ | CPU is missing at least one v2 instruction (likely SSE4.2 or POPCNT) |\n| **Windows Arm64 (SQ1)** | ✅ | Different architecture — x86 baseline doesn't apply |\n| **Raspberry Pi 4 (Arm64 Linux)** | ✅ | Different architecture — unaffected |\n\n## How to confirm\n\nOn the failing node, check which instructions it actually supports:\n\n```bash\ngrep -oP 'flags\\s*:\\s*\\K.*' /proc/cpuinfo | head -1 | tr ' ' '\\n' | grep -E 'sse3|ssse3|sse4_1|sse4_2|popcnt|cx16'\n```\n\nIf any of those six are missing, that's your culprit.\n\n## Options\n\n1. **Retire/replace the hardware** — simplest path; the node is 13+ years old\n2. **Keep that node on .NET 10** (LTS) until it's decommissioned — .NET 10 still supports x86-64-v1\n3. **Build a custom runtime** from source with a lower baseline (`/p:RequiredInstructionSets=` override) — not recommended for production","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"27aeaaec-4969-484e-8ab2-6905a9ce5789","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge quest