But the user says the issue appeared after upgrading to .NET 11, not .NET 10, which suggests .NET 11 raised the bar even further—possibly from v2 to v3. That would explain why it worked before but broke now.\n\nI think the clearest explanation is that .NET 11 bumped up the x86-64 baseline requirement, and their 2012 hardware is missing some of the CPU instructions the new runtime demands. The fix would involve either upgrading the hardware, using a compatibility mode if available, or targeting a lower baseline. .NET 10 likely raised the baseline to x86-64-v2 (which Sandy Bridge supports), while .NET 11 probably went further to v3 (requiring AVX2, which 2012 hardware lacks). This would explain why the code worked fine on .NET 10 but broke immediately after upgrading. I'm not entirely certain about the exact version numbers for when these baseline changes happened, but the pattern fits perfectly with the user's experience. Some older AMD processors from that era might be missing SSE4.2 or other instructions required by x86-64-v2, which would explain why their 2012 hardware fails on .NET 11 while newer architectures like Arm64 work fine.","outputTokens":3146,"requestId":"E020:343DCA:BA94CB:DAB05B:69F405DC"},"id":"e2e520d8-62b4-4005-811b-bfddc50c36b1","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:47:10.455Z","parentId":"7c082eb4-c9d2-4f99-8921-b4d62ee439fc"}
